    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Podalyria parvifolia are flavonoids, particularly kaempferol and quercetin, which have been shown to exhibit potent antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial activities. The plant's leaves also contain phenolic acids, such as caffeic acid and ferulic acid, which have been demonstrated to possess anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties. The bark and roots of Podalyria parvifolia contain triterpenoid saponins, including 3-hydroxy-ursolic acid and 3-oxo-ursolic acid, which have been found to exhibit immunomodulatory and anti-inflammatory activities. Additionally, the plant's leaves contain tannins and glycosides, which have been reported to have antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties. The combination of these bioactive compounds in Podalyria parvifolia contributes to its traditional use in treating various ailments, including wounds, fever, and digestive disorders.",
